    java.lang.AutoCloseable
    public class Robot
extends edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.TimedRobot
    This is the top-level class where the TimedRobot states are defined.

    This project is focused on testing the new mechanical design features used during the robot design and build as well as getting experience with the swerve software. Most notably, the swerve drive control will be leveraging the provided WPILib swerve functionality and exteded with thePath Planner software for path following. Another big part to the software is the extensive use of the WPILib data logger. This is used to log telemetry and other useful data for analysis (failure prediction and understaning, system tuning, and etc). Be sure to always use a USB thumb drive while logging. To do this, be sure to format the thumb drive with a RoboRIO compatible FS (like FAT32) and simply plug into one of the two USB ports on the RoboRIO.

    The states are run based on IterativeRobotBase.loopFunc()

    This project uses the WPILib CommandScheduler. The CommandScheduler.run() method of the scheduler is called every iteration of the perdiodic loop.

    The REV Robotics pressure sensor can be used for closed-loop control per the 2022 FRC game rules.

    See Also:
    Path Planner, WPILib Logger

      • robotInit

        public void robotInit()
        This method is called only a single time when the robot is first powered on. This is where initialization code should go.

        1. Disable all of the LiveWindow telemetry since it's not used and having it only eats up bandwidth. For 2023 this should be the default of WPILib. Disable the command scheduler to keep the subsystems from logging data after initial boot-up. Exception will be handled on a case-by-case basis (like IMU).

        2. Instantiate the robot containter (this will create all of subsystems and commands) and other objects.

        3. Disable the compressor to keep it from turning on during autonomous. The path-following is tuned with the compressor off, so keep it off during auto to maintain accuracy.

        4. If the logger is being used, start the log manager and setup all of the log entries. Each of the subsystems will have their individual control and setup.

        5. Run the period methods of all subsystems. This will create all of the loggin objects used throughout the robot life-cycle.

        6. Finally, update the swerve module home offsets to account for any errors during robot setup (cannot assume 0).

        Overrides:
        robotInit in class edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.IterativeRobotBase

      • autonomousInit

        public void autonomousInit()
        This method is called only a single time at the start of autonomous. This is where the autonomous-specific initialization code should go.

        1. Enable the command scheduler. This will begin logging all of the subsytem telemetry, running the subsystem state machines, and processing commands.

        2. Get the autonomous command to run.

      • autonomousPeriodic

        public void autonomousPeriodic()
        This method is called every loop during autonomous. It is called prior to the robotPeriodic method and should contain autonomous-specific periodic code.

        1. Log the compressor current. This should be disabled, so the expectation are the measurements will all be 0 amps.

      • teleopInit

        public void teleopInit()
        This method is called only a single time at the start of teleop. This is where the teleop-specific initialization code should go.

        1. Enable the command scheduler. During match-play, it will already be enabled, but during driver practice and bring-up the auto cycle is rarely run.

        2. Enable the compressor.

      • robotPeriodic

        public void robotPeriodic()
        This method is called every loop during autonomous, teleop, and disabled. Periodic code which is common to all of these robot states should go here.

        1. Run the command scheduler. This will call the periodic methods of the subsystems, process the new driver and operator requests, and process current commands.

        2. Log the pressure and IMU yaw angle. These should be monitored throughout the whole life-cycle of the robot.

        3. Send the pressure and IMU yaw angle to the smart dashboard. These are two of the very few data which is useful to the drive team during match-play.

        Overrides:
        robotPeriodic in class edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.IterativeRobotBase
